An Analysis of the Relationship between Suicide Incidences and Suicide-related Media Coverage

Haruto Yano

2023-05-12

1 Introduction

This is a data analysis project in Macro Data Science class when I was a junior. In this project, I explore correlation between fluctuation in suicide and media report on suicide using data in Japan. Theres been phenomena that we find increase in suicide after media reports suicide of celebrity. This is called Werther effect or Copycat suicide. Especially, during covid-19 pandemic, we saw increase in suicide and some of them were reported by media. If we actually can observe the phenomenon, then policy maker and mass media have to take some measure to prevent news report from inducing suicide. My purpose here is to make it clear that whether we can find Werther effect. If you are not familier with time series data analysis, this paper helps you understand time series analysis briefly.

2 Data

I used the number of suicide data, Covid-19 confirmed case data from MHLW and unemployment rate data from MIC.

  • Suicide data

  • Covid-19 data

  • Unemployment data

Unemployment rate has been considered to be correlated with suicide rate. During recession period, unemployment rate rises and suicide rate rises accordingly. The reason I selected the number of Covid-19 case is that it correlated with period of state of emergency and during this period, some suicide cases were reported on the media.

2.3 Unit root test

We have to check whether each time series data has unit root. If a time series data has unit root, the data is called non-stationary. Estimating on non-stationary data leads to spurious relationship, so we need to distinguish stationary and non-stationary data. ADF, PP and KPSS are popular unit root test. As you can see in graph, some time series data potentially have structural break, which make it difficult to detect unit root correctly. So I tested unit root with Zivot-Andrew test that can take an effect of single structural break into account. Most of the ADF test,PP test and KPSS test results contradict each other especially in mens suicide data. Here, I prioritize ADF test result and I confirmed data of woman under 19 yaers old as I(1).

3 Model

As for study of suicide, you can choose different empirical models depending on your purpose. In this report, I adopted ARDL model because it can include both endogenous and exogenous variables with their lags and allow I(1) data to be included. The model is given by: \[ ln(S_{i,j,t}) = \alpha + \sum_{p=1}^{P} \beta_p ln(S_{i,j,t-p}) + \sum_{q=0}^{Q} \gamma_q ln(U_{i,t-q})+ \sum_{r=0}^{R} \delta_r ln(C_{t-r}) + \lambda_1 news_t + \lambda_2 month_t + \lambda_3 trend + \epsilon_t \] where

  • i,j,t represent gender, age, period respectively

  • S is the number of suicide

  • U is Unemployment rate

  • C is infection count

  • news is dummy for suicide reports

  • As a monthly dummy, I incorporated March and April dummy because in Japan, suicide case increases in spring. Look this site

The error correction model is given by: \[ \Delta ln(S_{i,j,t}) = \alpha + \sum_{p=1}^{P} \Delta \beta_p ln(S_{i,j,t-p}) + \sum_{q=0}^{Q} \gamma_q \Delta ln(U_{i,t-q})+ \sum_{r=0}^{R} \delta_r \Delta ln(C_{t-r}) + \theta_0 ln(S_{i,j,t-1}) + \theta_1 ln(U_{i,t-1}) + \theta_2 ln(C_{t-1}) + \lambda_1 news_t + \lambda_2 month_t + \lambda_3 trend + \epsilon_t \]

4 Result

4.1 Estimation result

I pick up only results where I can find 5% significance in suicide report dummy, which are 20s,30s,50s of men and 20s,40s,50s and 60s of women results. Although I could find correlation between suicide and suicide news, we must be careful to interpret the results. Looking at diagnostic test in Appendix, you can find model of wom_20s doesn`t pass normality test, model of man_50s doesnt pass serial correlation test, which means theres room for improvement in model specification. Moreover, coefficient of suicide_report1 in man_50s, suicide_report3 in wom_40s are negative with significance and its hard to explain these results.

5 Discussion

Although I could observe correlations between the number of suicide and media coverage on suicide, as I mentioned in section 4.1, theres issue in interpreting the result. One of the possible reason is that I incorrectly chose variables. For example, Covid-19 made it difficult to have interaction with people, which in turn worsen mental health of people. Considering that, I should have added pedestrian flow data as an index of peoples interaction. That said, I believe the number of infections in part correlate with peoples flow. Other than this, I had better have data about disease, which is one of the biggest reason for suicide. Other reason that makes result harder to interpret is identification issue. Since I adopted reduced form model, we are not able to take the coefficients of variables as net effect of data. Suppose the value of living against value of committing suicide is given by: \[ L(S_t) + \epsilon_{i0t} \] and value of committing suicide is defined by: \[ \alpha_i + \beta_i U_{it} + \gamma_iC_t + \xi_{t} + \lambda D_t + \epsilon_{it} \] where \(S_t\) is state variable at time t, \(D_t\) is dummy variables, \(i\) represent individual, \(\xi_{t}\) is unobserved shock and $ $ follows type I extreme distribution. Then people make decision of suicide if \[ \alpha_i + \beta_i U_{it} + \gamma_iC_t + \xi_{t} +\lambda D_t + \epsilon_{it} > L(S_t) + \epsilon_{i0t} \] and we can formulate probability of suicide as: \[ P(suicide) = \frac{exp(\alpha_i + \beta_i U_{it} + \gamma_iC_t + \xi_{t}+\lambda D_t)}{exp(L(S_t)) + exp(\alpha_i + \beta_i U_{it} + \gamma_iC_t + \xi_{t} + \lambda D_t))} \] If this is true model of suicide, coefficients of reduced form model dont show actual effect of unemployment rate or confirmed case. Future study should address identification issue as well as selection of appropriate variables.
